<TITLE> Iraq frees Shi'ites held over Kerbala clash </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KERBALA, Iraq, Jan 1 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iraqi police freed 51 followers of Shia cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, including a provincial council member, held over clashes in the Shia holy city of Kerbala last August, the police commander in the province said on Tuesday. The clashes between Sadr's followers and police in Kerbala during a Shi'ite pilgrimage sparked outrage in the Shi'ite community and prompted Sadr to order a ceasefire which US forces say contributed to a decline in violence countrywide. Police chief Brigadier-General Raid Shakir told Reuters that investigators had cleared the 51 Sadr supporters, including Sadr's representative on the provincial governing council Ahmed al-Hussainy, and they were released overnight. The investigation found that more than 95 people had been killed and 285 wounded during the August clashes in the holy city, he said. Amid the extensive destruction, the outer wall of a Shia shrine was damaged. US forces say attacks from Sadr's Mehdi Army militia have declined since Sadr ordered the ceasefire. The cleric's office has said he is considering whether to extend the truce when it expires in Februa
